column2: b'@rks2305 @BrianFeroldi $MEDS showed up on a screener I was running for growth. They have attractive fundamentals but the price pattern is Eh. I need to do a better thread on them and also present my case better (working in progress). Look at $AHCO as well https://t.co/0cUIjh8UoX'
b'@ChartingOptions $AHCO\n\nThanks!'

b"$AHCO \xf0\x9f\x93\x88242% YTD to $37.6 \xf0\x9f\x94\xa5

MA(50)=$32.3

Q3'20 YOY
Rev=$708M\xf0\x9f\x93\x8886%
P/L=$1.4M

Acquisitions:
AeroCare Holdings for $2B > respiratory/home med equipment
New England Home Med Equipment > expanding diabetes division
*Rev=$31M

'21 Outlook-Raised
Rev=$2.1B\xf0\x9f\x93\x88122% YOY
EBITDA=$480M

\xf0\x9f\x9a\xa8 https://t.co/dxYE4XyKAY"

b"However, at 6.5x '21 EBITDA and a 26.6 forward P/E, and with Medicare's competitive bidding process 

1) limiting competitors (# of supplier bids fell 48% from '13-'18)

and

2) providing attractive private market valuations for add-ons

$AHCO could be in for a strong 2021"

b'The proj. organic growth is only 8-10%, and EBITDA margins are at 18.5% currently (proj. 23.2% next year). Given the above, $AHCO will not receive a crazy multiple.\n\nI caution that I need to understand DMEPOS Medicare reimbursement better before starting a position.'

b"Obviously there is risk associated with executing this merger, but it provides $AHCO an entry into the SE US as well as further scale to their platform\n\nIt is very important to know that M&A is very important to scaling (Aerocare is $AHCO's 65th transaction since 2017)"

b"$AHCO: AdaptHealth is a durable medical equipment provider, recently completed a massive $2B acquisition (relative to $2.5B EV) of Aerocare, this acquisition is driving a proj. ~100% topline growth in '21 to revenues of >$2B."
